    "resolution_criteria": "In the upcoming Men's Winter Olympics Hockey game, scheduled for 2026-02-21:\nIf Slovakia win, the market will resolve to \"Slovakia\".\nIf Finland win, the market will resolve to \"Finland\".\nIf the game is postponed, this market will remain open until the game has been completed.\nIf the game is canceled entirely, with no make-up game, this market will resolve 50-50.\nThe result will be determined based on the final score including any overtime periods and shootouts. In the event of a shootout, one goal will be added to the winning team's score for the purpose of resolution.",
    "outcome": "Finland",
    "explanation": "\n## Executive Summary\nIn the bronze medal match of the 2026 Winter Olympics, Finland overwhelmingly defeated Slovakia 6-1 to secure the bronze medal. Despite suffering a 4-1 loss to Slovakia in the tournament's opening round-robin game, the Finnish squad demonstrated significant defensive improvement and offensive firepower in the rematch. A tight 2-1 contest was blown wide open midway through the third period, fueled by a dominant performance from goaltender Juuse Saros and a barrage of late goals, leading to the final 6-1 outcome.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **February 21, 2026 (Pre-game):** Finland and Slovakia faced off in the bronze medal game, marking a rematch of their opening tournament game which Slovakia won 4-1.\n- **February 21, 2026 (Early game):** Finland established an early lead with goals from Sebastian Aho and Erik Haula, keeping the score at a tight 2-1 through the first two periods [art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063].\n- **February 21, 2026 (3rd Period - 8:27):** Roope Hintz scored Finland's third goal, effectively breaking the game open [art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063].\n- **February 21, 2026 (Late 3rd Period):** Kaapo Kakko, Joel Armia, and an empty-net goal by Erik Haula added insurance markers, cementing the 6-1 victory [art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063].\n- **February 21, 2026 (Game-long):** Finnish goaltender Juuse Saros stopped 30 of 31 shots from Slovakia to stifle any comeback hopes [art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063].\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe outcome was initially rooted in Finland's strategic reset following their early tournament 4-1 loss to Slovakia. This early setback caused Finland to tighten their defensive structure significantly throughout the rest of the tournament. In the bronze medal game, this strong defensive foundation, spearheaded by goaltender Juuse Saros who turned aside 30 shots, prevented Slovakia from capitalizing on their offensive opportunities [art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063]. The proximate trigger for the blowout occurred in the third period; holding a narrow 2-1 lead, Roope Hintz's goal at the 8:27 mark demoralized the Slovakian defense. This pivotal moment led to a rapid sequence of insurance goals from Kakko, Armia, and Haula, resulting in the final 6-1 victory for Finland.\n\n## Countervailing Factors\nSlovakia entered the game with a psychological advantage, having decisively beaten Finland 4-1 in their first round-robin matchup. Additionally, Slovakian star Juraj Slafkovsky was having an outstanding tournament, generating significant offensive pressure. However, these advantages were nullified by Juuse Saros's stellar goaltending and Finland's impenetrable defensive scheme, preventing Slovakia from translating their early tournament momentum into a medal-winning performance.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- E1: Finland loses opening round-robin game to Slovakia 4-1.\n  - Date: Mid-February 2026\n  - Why it matters causally: Prompted Finland to adopt a stricter defensive posture for the remainder of the tournament.\n  - Source article IDs: art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063\n- E2: Roope Hintz scores the 3-1 goal in the third period.\n  - Date: 2026-02-21\n  - Why it matters causally: Broke the tight 2-1 game wide open, leading to a late offensive surge by Finland.\n  - Source article IDs: art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063\n- E3: Juuse Saros makes 30 saves against Slovakia.\n  - Date: 2026-02-21\n  - Why it matters causally: Kept Slovakia from gaining traction and maintained Finland's early lead.\n  - Source article IDs: art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Finland wins 6-1 | art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063 | 2026-02-21 | 1.0 | Clear final score reported. |\n| Juuse Saros stops 30 of 31 shots | art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063 | 2026-02-21 | 1.0 | Key defensive statistic driving the outcome. |\n| Roope Hintz goal at 8:27 of 3rd | art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063 | 2026-02-21 | 1.0 | Identified as the turning point of the game. |\n| Slovakia won the first matchup 4-1 | art_sports_20260221_004_56a60063 | 2026-02-21 | 1.0 | Context for the matchup. |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\n- If Juuse Saros had faltered early, Slovakia's potent offense led by Juraj Slafkovsky might have seized early momentum, replicating the 4-1 result from the group stages.\n- An alternate path exists where the game remains 2-1 into the final minutes, forcing a pulled goalie situation much earlier and potentially a different outcome if Slovakia equalized.\n",
